WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.640
We are all in great company here.

00:00:02.640 --> 00:00:06.800
I count myself as a package developer as well.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:13.040
And we write an R package, we want, chances are, we want to share it with as many people

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:14.600
as will find it useful.

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:17.240
We want it to see the light of day.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:23.520
And that brings us to the dreaded ordeal of publishing.

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:32.279
And that's something that we have in common with authors of books, of journal articles,

00:00:32.279 --> 00:00:36.619
and of other kinds of media that are published in general.

00:00:36.619 --> 00:00:43.459
We have the standard practices generally to go through a central publisher, like CRC Press

00:00:43.459 --> 00:00:48.959
for books or Journal of the American Statistical Association for journal articles.

00:00:48.959 --> 00:00:54.439
And for us, we have repositories like CRAN, Bioconductor, and ROpenSci.

00:00:54.439 --> 00:01:01.500
This is generally the best way to help our work see the light of day, to make sure people

00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:05.440
use it, to convince people to trust what we put out there.

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:09.279
But it comes with a challenge.

00:01:09.279 --> 00:01:16.080
Inherent to the model of central publishing, whether it's a book or article or package,

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:19.320
is editorial review.

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:24.879
And for sure, these review experiences can be extremely rewarding and edifying.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:32.599
But they also come with a lot of frustration and a long wait time to wait for feedback.

00:01:32.599 --> 00:01:37.519
And then there's ingesting that feedback, coming up with revisions, and you might even

00:01:37.519 --> 00:01:38.959
get rejected.

00:01:38.959 --> 00:01:44.000
Even if you don't get rejected, you might have to do something to your package that you

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:47.680
find difficult or maybe not even agree with.

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:55.320
And so, a lot of folks turn to self-publishing, which is possible, again,

00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:59.720
for books and journal articles and packages.

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:01.599
We all have ways of doing this.

00:02:01.599 --> 00:02:06.160
And the reasons we might want to do this is that, as package developers,

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:07.519
we control publishing.

00:02:07.519 --> 00:02:10.320
No one has to tell us what to do.

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:13.600
The freedom is really nice, but it comes at a cost.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:19.440
Again, this other extreme of the trade-off, because we have a hard time convincing users

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:20.639
to trust our work.

00:02:20.639 --> 00:02:25.279
If on a self-published repository, as a user, I might express more skepticism

00:02:25.279 --> 00:02:29.080
of something that's self-published rather than something that's formally vetted

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:31.320
in a central repository.

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:35.639
And also, your work is harder to find if you self-publish.

00:02:35.639 --> 00:02:39.080
And speaking of obscurity, let's talk a little bit about siloing.

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:46.240
If I'm a user and I install a package from GitHub or even from our universe,

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:49.279
not only do I need to know the name of each package I want to install,

00:02:49.279 --> 00:02:53.440
I need to know every package's individual repository.

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:58.800
And for a user with hundreds of downloaded installed packages on my system,

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:03.199
I don't want to have to do that for every single one.

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:10.440
Which brings me to R Multiverse, which is a new dual repository built on top

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:12.800
of the R Universe project.

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:18.880
And what it aims to do is provide a centralized place for self-published

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:24.240
releases, and on top of that, automated checks and quality control

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:25.800
for production scenarios.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:31.520
What we're trying to do is meet this middle ground to try to combine the best

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:38.800
of both worlds of self-publishing and centralized publishing with review.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:42.720
Now, let's get into how this works.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:45.399
With R Multiverse, it's very new.

00:03:45.399 --> 00:03:50.800
It's a dual repository, so it's not just one repository, it's two.

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:55.279
And our first repository is this community repository.

00:03:55.279 --> 00:03:59.759
It's just plain and simple, an R Universe with all the latest releases

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:01.919
of registered packages.

00:04:01.919 --> 00:04:06.880
And on top of that, we have a production repository with quarterly snapshots

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:10.240
of the healthy releases from the community repository.

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:13.520
So my goal for the rest of this talk is to help you understand each

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:19.880
of these repositories, what they mean for users, and what they mean for developers

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:23.519
who want to participate and contribute packages.

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:27.160
So a bit about this community repository.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:31.399
So it's, like I said, plain and simple, an R Universe,

00:04:31.399 --> 00:04:33.559
just like any other R Universe.

00:04:33.559 --> 00:04:37.399
It's got a nice dashboard with package documentation, metrics,

00:04:37.399 --> 00:04:42.160
and test results, and it's transparently available.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:45.880
We have a nice custom URL for it, both for the dashboard and

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:48.160
for downloading packages.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:53.880
And the latest releases come directly from the individual source,

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:58.839
GitHub and GitLab repositories, just like any other universe does

00:04:58.839 --> 00:05:01.720
on the R Universe platform.

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:07.079
And the implications of this, because this is a single universe that is offered

00:05:07.079 --> 00:05:10.160
to the entire community to participate in.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:14.239
Usually, individual universes are maintained by individual users,

00:05:14.239 --> 00:05:16.799
individual labs, or individual developers, I should say,

00:05:16.799 --> 00:05:18.320
who want to publish their own work.

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:22.440
This is something that we all share, and it's also focused on releases.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:27.279
What that means is it's a middle ground between development on the one hand

00:05:27.279 --> 00:05:29.399
and production on the other.

00:05:29.399 --> 00:05:33.519
There's this term QA, or quality assurance, in industry and

00:05:33.519 --> 00:05:34.880
software development.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:38.839
And to my knowledge, we've never had this for R before,

00:05:38.839 --> 00:05:42.920
but that's exactly what this community repository aims to do.

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:44.239
It's this middle ground.

00:05:44.239 --> 00:05:49.440
It's releases that the developers endorse for production,

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:54.040
but are not necessarily ready for production because we don't enforce tests

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:57.959
or guarantees of compatibility at this level precisely.

00:05:57.959 --> 00:05:59.679
That's for production later on.

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:03.399
So, that's what the community repository is.

00:06:03.399 --> 00:06:08.160
You can imagine that you would want to install, maybe if I'm a user,

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:14.679
I would install a small number of packages from the community universe where I want

00:06:14.679 --> 00:06:18.079
just the latest and greatest from a small number of packages that I'm familiar

00:06:18.079 --> 00:06:23.000
with, that I trust, and developers can just very quickly and easily get releases

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:24.399
there very fast.

00:06:24.399 --> 00:06:28.399
So, that's where community sits here.

00:06:28.399 --> 00:06:32.959
Now, how do you, as a package developer, get your package into the community

00:06:32.959 --> 00:06:37.079
universe and registered with R multiverse in general?

00:06:37.079 --> 00:06:42.480
So, we keep our submission requirements very minimal at this level.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:48.119
So, we want to make this experience as close to self-publishing as we can.

00:06:48.119 --> 00:06:53.600
And so, what really this boils down to is the artifact that you register has

00:06:53.600 --> 00:07:00.040
to be an R package with at least one release on GitHub or GitLab.

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:05.720
It has to be devoid of malicious activity, has to be, you know,

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:10.720
in good faith and not have malware, et cetera, et cetera.

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:14.920
And it's got to have a free and open-source license and the most

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:16.040
obvious standard place.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:20.799
So, we, as the administrators of R multiverse, have permission

00:07:20.799 --> 00:07:23.160
to distribute the code.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:29.600
And so, all we're asking is that it's an R package and it's legal and safe.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:32.640
We do have policies, and there's maybe a bit more to than that,

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:37.279
but we generally take after the GitHub terms of service and acceptable

00:07:37.279 --> 00:07:38.160
use policies.

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:45.480
So, very straightforward and, you know, for well-meaning authors to abide

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:46.440
by this.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:52.119
And that is all we ask for registered packages in community.

00:07:52.119 --> 00:07:57.559
So, the registration procedure, again, is simple and it's open,

00:07:57.559 --> 00:07:58.760
it's open-source.

00:07:58.760 --> 00:08:05.119
We have this contributions repository with a collection of registered listings

00:08:05.119 --> 00:08:06.160
of packages.

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:10.359
And these are just text files where it's one text file per package and the text

00:08:10.359 --> 00:08:15.399
file usually has the URL of the source code repository of the package.

00:08:15.399 --> 00:08:20.040
And all you'll do is you'll go into the web interface, you will submit a pull

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:25.239
request to add a new text file where the title of the file is your package and the

00:08:25.239 --> 00:08:29.200
contents is just one line with the source code URL.

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:34.200
And then what happens in the pull request is there is a bot that runs about every

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:39.039
hour and it scans the pull requests and it just checks, is this a package?

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:40.440
Does it have a license?

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:44.599
Are there any conflicts with an existing package with the same name on CRAN,

00:08:44.599 --> 00:08:45.760
et cetera, et cetera?

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:49.840
And is the, you know, what do we know about, you know,

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:51.840
a couple other things related to that.

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:58.719
And if those very, very light checks pass and there's a high degree of trust,

00:08:58.719 --> 00:09:04.039
let's say the maintainer is a member of a trusted GitHub organization,

00:09:04.039 --> 00:09:08.719
then the bot can automatically merge and register the package.

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:12.200
In a lot of cases, you know, if there's some finding with a check,

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:15.719
it doesn't necessarily mean a rejection, it just means a manual review is

00:09:15.719 --> 00:09:16.239
required.

00:09:16.239 --> 00:09:21.640
And again, according to these very light submission requirements.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:26.280
Downstream of that, another automated process compiles all these listings and

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:30.799
automatically generates an R universe package manifest with, again,

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:37.760
the package URLs and it sets the branch field equal to star release.

00:09:37.760 --> 00:09:40.840
And what that means is instead of pulling the latest commit,

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:45.400
we're pulling the latest release off of GitHub and GitLab.

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:49.320
The implication of that is that new releases,

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:54.919
if you want to update a registered package that already exists in our multiverse,

00:09:54.919 --> 00:09:57.559
you do not have to go through human.

00:09:57.559 --> 00:10:01.359
You can just straightforwardly create a new release on GitHub.

00:10:01.359 --> 00:10:07.919
This is what a lot of us as package developers do anyway when we create a

00:10:07.919 --> 00:10:12.159
release of a package and we want to submit it to other standard repositories.

00:10:12.159 --> 00:10:16.840
It's great practice to create a release on GitHub and GitLab anyway.

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:22.919
And this is all that it takes to update a new version in the community repository.

00:10:22.919 --> 00:10:26.760
And then your package will be straightforwardly available to install.

00:10:27.039 --> 00:10:29.880
No matter what package is in community, again, for users,

00:10:29.880 --> 00:10:35.640
it's this one unified URL that users can install from with install.packages.

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:37.000
It's very simple and easy.

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:42.359
The dependencies might come from other repos like CRAN, and so

00:10:42.359 --> 00:10:47.239
this getOptionsRepos is useful to make sure the dependencies are also installed

00:10:47.239 --> 00:10:47.739
if needed.

00:10:49.479 --> 00:10:51.599
So that's the community repository.

00:10:52.599 --> 00:10:59.039
The production repository has in mind that we use R for

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:04.000
really tightly regulated, tightly controlled situations and

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.159
things that are not just exploratory analyses.

00:11:07.159 --> 00:11:11.080
We run R for high stakes analyses that really need to be correct and

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:13.320
based on software that we trust.

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:15.760
And that's what production is aimed at.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:19.599
And our approach is a bit like Debian.

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:24.520
Jeroen Ooms came up with the spark for this idea,

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:30.000
borrowing from Debian's philosophy of gradually building snapshots at intervals.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:36.359
And we're optimistic that this way of thinking will turn out to not only

00:11:36.359 --> 00:11:40.479
provide the same quality for users, but also provide the same convenience for

00:11:40.479 --> 00:11:41.039
developers.

00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:47.119
So how this works is we take quarterly snapshots of the community universe, and

00:11:47.119 --> 00:11:51.559
we only include healthy releases with healthy dependencies

00:11:51.559 --> 00:11:53.559
from that community universe.

00:11:53.559 --> 00:11:56.799
And we gradually build each snapshot from the ground up,

00:11:56.799 --> 00:12:02.200
gradually to give developers enough time to make the adjustments they need

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:08.200
leading up to a snapshot, and also to avoid last minute volatility and panic.

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:10.000
And I'll go over that in a bit more detail.

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:15.440
What we require from production, it's a bit more.

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:20.679
All the requirements of community apply, plus we enforce warnings and

00:12:20.679 --> 00:12:23.440
errors in R command check for Mac, Linux, and Windows.

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:30.640
For a particular version of R, we require that the version number of

00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:35.479
the current release is higher than the others, so this is a benefit for users.

00:12:35.479 --> 00:12:40.440
And we also require that the dependencies of this package in our multiverse

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:42.000
also pass the same checks.

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:47.760
Our universe actually has this really nice feature that as soon as the checks

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:51.760
of a package are finished, all the downstream packages of degree one that

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:56.000
depend on it in the same universe are also rechecked.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.400
And what our multiverse does is it waits for those checks to complete, and

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:04.080
effectively what that means is we have the same reverse dependency check

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:08.280
guarantees that we're used to and that we rely on, but

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:10.520
coming at it from a different operating model.

00:13:12.159 --> 00:13:17.359
Now, our operating model is kind of looks like this in terms of

00:13:17.359 --> 00:13:20.159
where do we want to go with a snapshot and what does it look like?

00:13:20.159 --> 00:13:25.799
We want a collection of releases from our multiverse set in stone,

00:13:25.799 --> 00:13:30.520
built on a particular version of base R, and

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:33.479
a snapshot of packages from CRAN also set in stone.

00:13:34.559 --> 00:13:37.880
That's where we want to arrive at, and

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:43.119
what we end up starting with is not a pyramid of stone,

00:13:43.119 --> 00:13:48.200
more like a pyramid of water, where any package could change at any time.

00:13:48.200 --> 00:13:52.440
That's where we start, and we gradually freeze this ecosystem from the ground up,

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:55.760
and we start by fixing a version of base R and

00:13:55.760 --> 00:13:59.840
a snapshot of CRAN packages from Posit Public Package Manager.

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:05.000
And we say, those aren't gonna change for the entirety of the snapshot, and

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.280
we give an entire month for developers to adjust their packages and checks.

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:13.559
And after that, we start to freeze in the next month

00:14:13.559 --> 00:14:16.200
the packages that already work in multiverse.

00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:21.599
We freeze the healthy packages, and we give time for bugs to be fixed.

00:14:21.599 --> 00:14:25.640
So, and this is a gradual, nice, soft landing and

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:30.640
soft freeze that allows the changes that enforce quality to happen, but

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:32.559
we provide stability along the way.

00:14:33.559 --> 00:14:37.400
And what we end up with is maybe not all the packages from community, but

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:39.159
certainly a lot of them.

00:14:39.159 --> 00:14:44.880
And it's this nice model that guarantees this compatibility of

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:48.479
the packages and their dependencies in this ecosystem.

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:56.080
And for user installing from production, you would supply a dated snapshot URL,

00:14:56.080 --> 00:15:00.359
and the Posit Public Package Manager snapshot from two months prior.

00:15:00.559 --> 00:15:06.359
And so to recap, so multiverse tries to centralize these releases and

00:15:06.359 --> 00:15:10.799
enforce quality for users, but also puts power and

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:17.919
control in the hands of the maintainers to make it as much like self-publishing as we can.

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:23.640
And why I'm talking with all of you is this is the debut of multiverse.

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:29.599
We are ready to scale, and we are inviting package contributions from all of you.

00:15:29.599 --> 00:15:34.280
And we also wanna scale up the moderator team to make sure that

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:38.080
this reviewing experience is fast and simple.

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:41.799
So if you'd like to participate as a moderator as well, please come talk to me.

00:15:43.359 --> 00:15:47.919
I maintain multiverse with three other folks listed here, and

00:15:47.919 --> 00:15:54.239
we couldn't have done this without the R Consortium or R OpenSci, or R Universe.

00:15:54.239 --> 00:15:57.000
Thanks very much, and I will be happy to take questions.

00:15:57.700 --> 00:16:15.780
It's a great question.

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:19.900
So we check against the R Consortium advisory database which

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:22.859
exists to report security findings.

00:16:22.859 --> 00:16:26.179
We check new submissions against that database and

00:16:26.179 --> 00:16:28.659
we enforce that again in production.

00:16:28.659 --> 00:16:33.219
I didn't list that check in the slides because it's not new or

00:16:33.219 --> 00:16:35.739
in the sense it's not unique to production, but we do enforce that.

00:16:35.739 --> 00:16:41.239
Okay, so injecting maybe a

00:16:41.239 --> 00:16:56.760
package with a similar name, but

00:16:56.760 --> 00:17:04.199
enough like an existing package, but that might do something nefarious.

00:17:04.199 --> 00:17:08.760
The advisory databases as well, we rely on that stuff.

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:11.680
We rely on the community report to report those findings.

00:17:12.760 --> 00:17:18.400
We also have, for most package submissions, we have a manual review process.

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:21.160
And in terms of automatically accepting packages,

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:26.959
we take a people first approach to safety rather than a package first.

00:17:26.959 --> 00:17:31.719
So there's a short list of trusted organizations like R OpenSci,

00:17:31.719 --> 00:17:37.119
R Consortium, and we're open to growing that list.

00:17:37.119 --> 00:17:43.599
But also, if a developer isn't part of one of those trusted organizations,

00:17:43.599 --> 00:17:46.400
then we always do a manual review of new packages.

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:50.439
And we've thought about automated checks on, let's say,

00:17:50.439 --> 00:17:54.239
the fuzzy matching of the name and stuff to account for that kind of spoofing, but

00:17:54.239 --> 00:17:55.199
haven't implemented that yet.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.359
Great work.

00:17:57.359 --> 00:17:58.060
Thank you.

00:17:58.060 --> 00:17:59.859
All right.

00:17:59.859 --> 00:18:01.280
Thank you.

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:05.839
Thank you.

00:18:06.959 --> 00:18:08.020
All right.

00:18:08.020 --> 00:18:08.800
Thank you.

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:11.560
Great work.

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:12.939
Thank you.

00:18:12.939 --> 00:18:13.939
Thank you.

00:18:13.939 --> 00:18:18.020
Thank you.

